<br>
Belana: “We have to go back.  Cendarien’s in trouble!”<br>
<br>
Inien: “We can’t go back.  He will have to fend for himself for the moment.”<br>
<br>
Belana: “What?”<br>
<br>
Inien: “I can’t just port to that spot Belana.  You know that.  The closest we could go would be the Dreadlands.”<br>
<br>
Belana: “What are you waiting for then, lets go!”<br>
<br>
Inien turned away from her and began to walk away from the spires.<br>
<br>
Belana: “What are you doing?”<br>
<br>
Inien stopped and turned around.  He opened his mouth as if to say anything but he didn’t.  He looked up into the sky through the mighty branches of the trees of the Faydark.  He could sense Belana’s urgency, and he understood it.  The pulsing of the spires echoed in his ears.  A sound only Inien or any other master wizard could here.  Its sound drowned out most of the surrounding noise around him.<br>
<br>
Belana stood there.  She was breathing heavy still from her yelling at Inien.  Her drive to save her husband was to strong for her to make any kind of rational decision.<br>
<br>
Inien: “I’m sorry Belana.”  And with that one phrase Inien disappeared.<br>
<br>
Belana ran forward to catch him but it was to late.  He was gone.  She searched the grounds around her to see if he might have somehow just moved to a different spot.  She called out his name but her only reply was the rustling of the leaves around her.  The sky was beginning to turn to dusk.  Crickets and other nightly creatures were beginning to sing their nocturne of the night.  She could feel her breathing steady, but with every breath she began to lose hope, but anger quickly filled that void.  Belana sat down.  She thumbed the hilts on her daggers nervously and steadily.  Her thoughts were clouded with somehow saving Cendarien but also of running Inien through.  Belana’s anger began to bubble over to the point where rage sat in.  An emotion she rarely used, and she couldn’t bare it.  She screamed at the top of her voice sending some of the animals around her to flee.<br>
<br>
The remaining light slowly disappeared leaving Belana alone.  The thoughts of many ideas passed to quickly through her head for her to act on any of them.<br>
<br>
She fell backwards, letting the long grass absorb her body.  Hiding her from the events that surrounded her.  She only wished she could disappear like Inien  had just done.  Disappearing from the events around her.<br>
<br>
Then a thought hit her.  She cursed herself for not thinking of it sooner.  She had lost Inien’s guidance and Cendarien’s protection, but she hadn’t lost one thing that she had once held most dear to her.<br>
<br>
She picked herself up from the ground and began to walk towards Felwithe.<br>
<br>
<br>
Aaeon looked towards the horizon and watched the sun set behind the hills of Qeynos.  She had been on her watch now for almost four hours and without any incident.  Zaboxx or Phelsuma never said a word to her the whole time and she almost wondered if they were still there.  They made no evidence of walking behind her or even being in the same vicinity of her.<br>
<br>
Aaeon whispered: “Zaboxx?”<br>
<br>
There was no reply.<br>
<br>
Aaeon: “Phelsuma, are you guys there?”<br>
<br>
Again, there was no reply.  She moved her hand down towards her sword and grabbed the hilt.  She felt more confident knowing that if foul play was involved she wouldn’t be caught with her guard down.  She was a paladin, a proud and strong warrior.  She gained more strength in thinking of her training.  The skills and exercises she had to learn in order for her to gain this position in the paladin guild.<br>
<br>
The guard tower in Qeynos Hills was just noticeable in the distance.  Her thirst was beginning to creep up on her.  She withdrew her water flask but noticed she had forgot to fill it before she left.  She hadn’t planned on marching over to the tower but she hadn’t planned on having a pair of invisible shadows follow her around, and ignore her on top of it.<br>
<br>
The darkness began to roll across the hills and Aaeon’s sight began to lessen as the darkness passed her by.  She quickly casted her Infravision spell and soon the night became day in her eyes.<br>
<br>
She glanced in the direction of the tower and could see the torches were beginning to be lit one by one around the base.  Aaeon thought back on the first time she actually manned the guard tower in Qeynos Hills and spilled the fluid they dipped the torches into to keep them lit all night.  She had to keep manually wrapping the torches with the cloth they used so that other travelers could see it and come within the safe confines of the tower.  She laughed at herself.<br>
<br>
“What’s so funny?”<br>
<br>
Aaeon jumped: “I thought you left me.”<br>
<br>
Zaboxx: “We did.  There was something Phel and I had to take care of real quick.”<br>
<br>
Aaeon: “And what was that?”<br>
<br>
Phelsuma: “Don’t worry about it.  Was something very,” Phelsuma searched for a word, “unimportant.”<br>
<br>
Aaeon sensed that they weren’t being honest with her, “What was this unimportant feet then?”<br>
<br>
Zaboxx raised his voice: “It was nothing Aaeon.  It is best you don’t ask again.”<br>
<br>
Aaeon didn’t reply.  She became ever more suspicious of her comrades.<br>
<br>
They had finally made it to the guard tower where two guards were standing in front of the front door.<br>
<br>
Guard: “Hail Aaeon!”<br>
<br>
Aaeon: “Hail.  I come to replenish my water supply.”<br>
<br>
Guard: “It is behind us inside.  Feel free to help yourself young paladin.”<br>
<br>
Aaeon: “Thank you.”  Aaeon walked between the two guards and inside to the ration of water resting against the wall.  She removed her flask and submerged it into the tub of water.  Aaeon watched her flask fill with water.<br>
<br>
Then a scream shot from behind her.  She turned around to see one of the guards clutching a sword that had been run through his abdomen.  She quickly withdrew her sword and ran forward only to be met by Phelsuma.<br>
<br>
Aaeon: “Out of my way.  Were under attack.”<br>
<br>
Phelsuma: “I know.”<br>
<br>
Zaboxx appeared behind Aaeon and bashed the back of Aaeon’s head with his steel gauntlets knocking her to the ground.  Aaeon’s vision became groggy.  Zaboxx reached down and withdrew the long sword that Aaeon had brought with her.<br>
<br>
The other guard appeared from the doorway clutching a wound on his chest.  He withdrew his steel.  Zaboxx stood up with Aaeon’s weapon.  Phelsuma approached the guard.  The guard attempted to strike Phelsuma but his wound had weakened him.  Phelsuma easily countered it and pushed the guard to the ground.  Zaboxx walked over tossing the sword up into the air and grabbing it with the point facing towards the guard.  With a quick stroke the broad side of the blade struck the guard on the head laying him motionless on the ground.  Zaboxx walked over towards Aaeon who was still laying on the ground.<br>
<br>
Zaboxx: “It’s a pity.”<br>
<br>
Aaeon mumbled: “What are you doing?”<br>
<br>
Zaboxx: “You had such good potential Aaeon.  You looked as if you had such great potential.  But, Lord Innorruk deems you a threat.”<br>
<br>
Aaeon: “I don’t understand.”<br>
<br>
Zaboxx: “It’s quite simple really.  We were sent hear to get rid of you.  And that’s what were doing.”<br>
<br>
Zaboxx brought the sword down and the scream of metal piercing armor echoed inside the tower.<br>
