<br>
Belana found herself at the gates to Felwithe.  She motioned to the two guards outside.  The guards dressed in the golden armor removed their weapons from her path and let her pass through.<br>
<br>
She came to the bridge in the city and looked across a figure across the bridge staring back at her.  The figure slowly walked across the bridge and found his cover lost by the light of the moon up in the sky.  It was Kelwin.<br>
<br>
Belana walked forward and met him.  The both glanced at each other quickly and it was Belana first to break the silence.<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;It has been a long time Kelwin.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;Yes, it has.&quot;  He found her clothes dirty and tattered.  &quot;What happened to you?&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;I am okay.  It is Cendarien that is in trouble.  We need to get to Kunark to save him.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin frowned and shook his head: &quot;I told him this would happen.&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;What do you mean?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;Belana, you have been, pardon the reference, but rogue from us from some time.  It seems you have had matters greater than what this guild might have to offer.&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;My needs are not great.  I'm asking that we gather some of the Shadows to come to Kunark to rescue him.  That is indeed in our power.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;No.  You don't understand.&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana stared wild eyed into Kelwin.  Kelwin met her stare with his own sterness.  She could see and allready knew what he was going to tell her before he told her.<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;Don't say you can't help.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;With you and Inien both coming and going at will it is hard to keep order amongst the Shadows of the Ebon Moon.  You, took an oath when you became an elder to forgo any dealings outside the Shadows.  It has been more than time for you to deal with the death of your sister.  Your need is requested.&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;I don't understand.  We need to save Cendarien and you repeating the pledge I took.  I am not a fool Kelwin.  I swore to you and to the other Shadows that I would carry the burden of the Shadows and fight to keep those that would hurt it at bay.&quot;  Belana could barely keep her temper down, &quot;You speak of my sister as if it would be comparable to loosing a carriage or a home do to an attack or fire.  She is something I can't replace ever.  Bartel's magic couldn't bring her back.  Her faith in this guild was just as great.  She died for me and I can't let that go.  If giving up my eldership to somebody else is what you want then damnit Kelwin ... &quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;Stop!&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana stopped with her rant.  She was breathing heavy and steaming with rage.  Her control was gone.<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;You took the oath and you agreed.  I am not using your sister as a way of getting rid of you or having you hand down your eldership.  This guild means just as much to me as it does to you but I, not you, not Inien, nor anyone in this guild can possibly fathom what I have to do to keep this guild in running order.  I burden a responsibility that weighs upon me greatly and when I ask for simple favors they are never heeded.  I told Cendarien that he would fall into trouble if he tailed you and he did.  I warned him, yet he did not listen.  What is a guild without a leader.  Let me ask you that.  I ask that you come back for a simple meeting and I'm answered with your empty chair.  I am the one that has to explain to everyone if you'll ever be back.  Sorine has asked countless times if you'll be returning and Bartel is still guilt ridden by not being able to bring your sister back to life.  I haven't heard from him since you left.  You see Blackpoint Sorrowblade, we need you!&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana interrupted: &quot;You need me!  I need you!  I ask you for a simple favor of saving one of our own.  Cendarien is your likeness, a brother to the guild, and my soul mate to myself.  Pardon if he or my sister gives you the impression that there more important the Shadows but believe me, I have longed for the day to return, but these extenuating circumstances are making it impossible for me to do it.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin and Belana both stood in the center of the bridge.  Their expressions were placid.  Then a smile came across Belana's face.  Kelwin followed.<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;Ha! I can't belive I just yelled at you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;Nor I.&quot;<br>
<br>
Belana: &quot;So, now what?&quot;<br>
<br>
Kelwin: &quot;Well, either we can make peace or we part our separate ways.&quot;<br>
<br>
