( In a hut far from civilization )<br>
<br>
“I really don’t get it Muffin?  Why would Belana’s sister be undead?  I can’t seem to figure it out.”  Inien paced in his study.  The books of many pages of Lore were stacked all over the room.  A couple were open on a desk and some on the floor.  His happy imp companion Muffin, was flapping in his footsteps following his every move.  “I can’t believe that Whitepoint would do anything that would harm Belana or myself.  The only way I can see her ever doing something like this is if. . .”  Inien stopped thinking out loud.  A knock at his door stopped him.  He stopped pacing.  “Now who could be knocking at my door.”<br>
<br>
Inien walked over towards the door, “Who is it?”<br>
<br>
“It is I, Phelsuma.”<br>
<br>
Inien thought in his head, “How does she know I’m out here.  No one knows of this place.”  He grabbed the handle to the door and opened it.  His next vision was of a great fire radiating towards him.<br>
<br>
<br>
( Back in Felwithe )<br>
<br>
Kelwin and Belana stood in front of each other.<br>
<br>
“The answer is obvious Kelwin,” Belana answered.<br>
<br>
“And that would be,” Kelwin became placid to absorb the next words Belana would say, but he never heard them.  A sudden pain in his back rang loud in his body.  He felt himself pushed forward by the blow and fell against Belana.  Belana stepped back to catch Kelwin in her arms.  She looked behind him and could see a single arrow that had pierced his lower back.  Belana slowly lowered Kelwin to the ground.  Another arrow shot through the air and stuck into the dirt path just to the left of Belana.<br>
<br>
Kelwin gasped in pain, “Get, get out of here.”<br>
<br>
“That’s impossible,” Belana returned.<br>
<br>
Kelwin grimaced in pain as he tried to grab the shaft of the arrow.  Belana looked in the direction of where the second arrow came from and could see a dark figure on top of a building with a bow drawn up again.  Belana pushed Kelwin out of the way as she dived to her right.  The arrow pierced the ground where they had just sat.  Kelwin rolled over onto the arrow breaking the shaft in half.  The arrow dug itself deeper into his body.<br>
<br>
“Go!  Leave me,” Kelwin screamed.<br>
<br>
A guard fully armed in plate armor with spear and shield drawn saw Kelwin on the ground and began to run towards the two.  He arrived at the spot and looked down at Kelwin and Belana.  He opened his mouth to speak but no words were spoken.  An arrow sung out again and struck the guard between the chestplate and his helmet sending him the ground.<br>
<br>
Belana danced to her feet and grabbed the shield that the dead guard had been carrying.  She crawled over quickly and shielded Kelwin from their attacker.<br>
<br>
“You don’t listen very well do you?” Kelwin tried to hide the pain but it was becoming impossible.<br>
<br>
“I don’t know what it is with you elves.  Your always willing to die for the greater cause,” Belana felt the impact of another arrow hit the shield and reflect off.  “While I’m willing to live just to see tomorrow.”  Belana smiled down at Kelwin.<br>
<br>
“If that was a joke, that was a poor one,” Kelwin replied.<br>
<br>
Belana felt another arrow jolt the shield.  She was beginning to wonder if their assailant would ever come down and face them in person.  Another arrow struck the shield sending a shutter through Belana’s body.<br>
<br>
Their assailant finally walked down from the roof.  It threw the bow to the ground below and jumped down to ground level.  Belana peeked out and could see their attacker dressed in full plate, but it wasn’t like most.  It was made of a darker metal.  A metal that she had seen many times, the metal of a full suit of Dark Elven armor.<br>
<br>
“Blackpoint!  Come out from behind that shield!”<br>
<br>
Belana looked down at Kelwin who had passed out from the pain of the arrow.  She checked his breathing quickly and could feel shallow breaths.  She poked her head out once more and could see the figure drawing its weapon.  A single edged sword.   A sword she had seen many times.  She stood up from behind the mighty kite shield and revealed herself.<br>
<br>
She pulled her trusty daggers from inside her boots and walked forward towards her assailant.  Belana recognized who it was.<br>
<br>
“There, that’s a good girl.  Come, let us see who the better of us is at last.”<br>
<br>
Belana stopped, both of her blades were drawn, “Zaboxx, I have no idea what your doing but I can’t stand for this.”<br>
<br>
Zaboxx answered, “Its okay Blackpoint, you won’t be standing for much longer.”<br>
